Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotype networks describe relationships between individuals in populations and may be based on haplotype DNA sequence information or other molecular markers such as indels or microsatellites.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Given HW equilibrium in a population, gene frequencies and genotype frequencies will stay the same from generation to generation and can be predicted from the binomial expansion. Genotype frequencies are p2  2pq  q2  1 for autosomes; allele frequencies are p+q=1
explainConcepts[SQ003] Natural selection results in a change in population allele frequencies over time. Selection may be stabilizing selection which occurs when homozygotes are at a selective disadvantage compared to heterozygotes (sickle cell anemia), directional in which a specific allele frequency increases as a result of selection or disruptive in which selection is against heterozygotes.
phenomenonA Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonA[comment] White skin color in Europeans was a selective sweep to a single allele for skin color in response to vitamin D deficiency.
phenomenonB Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonB[comment] Sickle cell anemia is an example of heterozygous advantage where homozygotes tend to die from malaria or sickle cell anemia

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A haplotype network show the relationship among haplotypes which are a set of DNA variations that tend to be inherited together.
explainConcepts[SQ002] By plugging in the frequency of two different alleles dominant (p) and recessive (q) into the formula (p+q)^n=1 where n equals the number of alleles you can calculate the frequency of homozygous dominant, homozygous recessive, and the frequency of heterozygous individuals in a population.
explainConcepts[SQ003] If the criteria for HW equilibrium are not met them populations are evolving through things like natural selection, genetic drift, gene flow, or mutation.
phenomenonA Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonA[comment] The sickle cell anemia gene continues to exist in populations in Africa due to natural selection because this gene if heterozygous in an individual will help them to survive malaria. Because this selection is taking place HW equilibrium is not met.
phenomenonB The frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes can be predicted using the binomial expansion.
phenomenonB[comment] If one in twelve men are color blind then the frequency of color blind women is (1/12)^2 following binomial expansion p^2+2pq+q^2. Where p equals the frequency of homozygous women.

knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand this to be a condition that is not met in order for HW equilibrium to happen. This condition is the other way that the population is evolving by. The condition could be natural selection, genetic drift, gene flow, or mutation.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand this to be all the alleles that are present in a population. These alleles can be passed from organism to organism throughout the generations independently. However, things such as natural selection, genetic drift, or gene flow usually dictate how the alleles to various genes will be passed from generation to generation.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A haplotype is a unique set of genetic code. Individuals possessing the same haplotypes can be inferred to be related. This information can create haplotype networks.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Binomial expansion can be used to create a prediction of allele, genotype, and phenotype frequency based on the total number of alleles in a population, so long as the population adheres to the Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium conditions.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Populations that are not in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium are being effected by other evolutionary tactics that are impacting the allele, genotype, and phenotype frequencies. Such tactics include mutations, natural selection, gene flow, and genetic drift.
phenomenonA Haplotype networks
phenomenonA[comment] Haplotype networks can be used to determine the closeness in relationship between populations.
phenomenonB Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonB[comment] Populations affected by cystic fibrosis have a higher frequency of cystic fibrosis than as predicted as the Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, indicating that other evolutionary factors are at work.
groupTime421 640.74

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that a haplotype is a unique set of genetic code. I understand that individuals possessing the same haplotypes can be inferred to be related. I understand that this information can be used to create haplotype networks, which can illustrate the closeness in relationship between populations.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that binomial expansions can be tailored to the number of alleles in a population. I understand that these varying levels of binomial expansion can then be used to predict the frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes. I understand, for example, that for two alleles, p^2 + 2pq + q^2 = 1 would be used as an expansion of (p + q = 1)^2.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that it is very rare for a population to be in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium and produce allele and genotype frequencies consistent with the binomial expansion equations. I understand that natural selection, mutation, genetic drift, and gene flow lead to evolution but move a population out of Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that a gene pool is the makeup of all alleles in a population. I understand that homozygous dominant individuals contribute two dominant alleles each, homozygous recessive individuals contribute two recessive alleles, and that heterozygous individuals contribute one dominant and one recessive allele. I understand that gene pools may change over time via evolutionary tactics such as natural selection, mutation, genetic drift, and gene flow.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotype networks show the relationship of a population in terms of gene sequences. Haplotype is a group of alleles that are inherited as a unit; looking at a network of haplotypes in a population or in populations over time can show relations within a population and lineages over time.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Binomial expansion calculates the probability of a specific outcome involving two separate events within the outcome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Hardy-Weinburg assumptions are: no mutation, no migration, infinite population size, no natural selection, and random mating. If a population meets all the requirements, it is not evolving. Naturally, a population cannot meet these requirements, and thus, evolution takes place. Mutation produces new alleles and migration brings new alleles into a population, both increasing genetic diversity.
phenomenonA Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonA[comment] I think an interesting study regarding migration would involve looking at the genes of a population before travel was prevalent. Migration patterns between continents and between populations on the same continent are reflected through gene frequencies.
phenomenonB The frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes can be predicted using the binomial expansion.
phenomenonB[comment] Using binomial expansion, the probability of me having five boys and one girl is 15.6%.
groupTime421 2139.92

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that a haplotype sequence present in a population indicates a close relationship between individuals. I do not understand how to interpret an illustration of the network.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand the probability is calculated through the binomial expansion equation and I feel very comfortable finding probabilities for various sets of events using the equation; however, I do not know how the equation works mathematically.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that the Hardy-Weinburg equilibrium means the population is not evolving, and the assumptions restrict a population from evolving. I am not sure how this applies to real populations that are evolving. Understand that if allele frequency deviates from the frequency found using p^2+2pq+q^2, assumptions have been violated.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that gene pools are made up of the all the alleles in a population. Gene pools contain the genetic information that is expressed and not expressed in a population. Gene pools are largely heterozygous and genetically diverse. The extent of genetic diversity of gene pools may vary from population to population.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotype networks are a neat and concise way of organizing and representing the genetic differences between different groups of organisms. They display the relative genetic closeness of certain organisms based on how many different haplotypes they have.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Using different variables to represent different alleles, binomial expansion can be used to estimate allele frequencies, and thus the frequency of certain genotypes and phenotypes. Pascal's triangle can be used to find the appropriate binomial equation for a given gene. A common example of binomial expansion as related to genetics is the Hardy-Weinberg equation.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The Hardy Weinberg equation makes five assumptions: that the population is infinitely large, that mating is random, that there is no natural selection, that there are no mutations, and that there is no migration. In nature, virtually all of this conditions are continuous broken, resulting in allele frequencies that do not follow the Hardy-Weinberg predictions.
phenomenonA The frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes can be predicted using the binomial expansion.
phenomenonA[comment] We have learned about this concept before in this very course. In our discussion section activities, we have been asked to predict the likelihood of a certain couple having a child with cystic fibrosis, and we used a modified binomial expansion formula to solve the problem: (n!/(s!t!))x(a^s)x(b^t). Also, I remember binomial expansion and Pascal's triangle from my high school math courses. There, they never really taught us any application for it, so it's actually pretty cool to see real-life usefulness.
phenomenonB Haplotype networks
phenomenonB[comment] Hapolotype networks closely mirror phylogenetic trees in terms of function (but not really structure).

I understand how this purpose is extremely useful for measuring different alleles within a gene pool. Once you know the frequency of the different alleles, you can begin to predict the frequency of different genotypes and phenotypes, and once you have this information, you can compare it to observed data in a genetics study, and this will give you an idea of the evolutionary forces acting on a population.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand the five assumptions (listed on the previous page of the survey) that are necessary to the Hardy-Weinberg equation. I also understand why these assumptions are necessary: because no mathematical formula can accurately predict the direction and results of evolutionary forces. That is simply too complicated, because there are so many factors at play. Therefore, all formulas must make certain compromises and assume some of those factors are constant.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotype networks show how DNA is related among indviduals. It also shows how the DNA differs between individuals and what gene has the variations. These variations are determined by SNPs (single nucleotide polymorphisms) which is a single base change in DNA.
explainConcepts[SQ002] There are different equations that help to determine the frequency of alleles and genotypes. The letter "p" is used to describe the frequency of the dominant allele and "q" is used to describe the frequency of the recessive allele. p + q will always equal 1. We can use this to determine frequencies of genotypes as well using the equation p^2 + 2pg + q^2. p^2 is the frequency of the homozygous dominant genotype, q^2 is the frequency of the homozygous recessive genotype, and 2pq is the frequency of the heterozygous genotype.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Hardy Weinburg Equilibrium states that allele/genotypic frequencies stay the same from generation to generation. If the frequencies stay the same, the population will not be evolving. For a population to be evolving, the allele/genotypic frequencies will be moving in various directions for different genes.
phenomenonA The frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes can be predicted using the binomial expansion.
phenomenonA[comment] Using the frequencies of alleles, we can determine what the frequencies will be in future generations.
phenomenonB Haplotype networks
phenomenonB[comment] Haplotype networks can be used to see the origins of similar DNA from individuals and how it has migrated.

knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that Hardy Weinberg equilibrium assumes the allele/genotypic frequencies stay the same throughout generations. I understand that HWE assumes there is no mutation, selection, or migration and the populations must be infinitely large. I understand evolving populations must have changing allele/genotypic frequencies in one direction or another.

knowlegeBasis[SQ002] To estimate the frequency of alleles in a population, we can use the Hardy-Weinberg equation. According to this equation: p = the frequency of the dominant allele (represented here by A) q = the frequency of the recessive allele (represented here by a) For a population in genetic equilibrium: p + q = 1.0 (The sum of the frequencies of both alleles is 100%.) (p + q)2 = 1 so p2 + 2pq + q2 = 1 The three terms of this binomial expansion indicate the frequencies of the three genotypes: p2 = frequency of AA (homozygous dominant) 2pq = frequency of Aa (heterozygous) q2 = frequency of aa (homozygous recessive)
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Frequency of alleles in gene pool does not change over time. Hardy Weinber model assumes Equal rate of survival and reproduction (no selection)No new alleles arise or created by mutation No migration,into or out of population,Infinitely large population, Random mating occurs
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] A gene pool is a collection of all the genes in a population. This can be any population. Gene pool can change if random matting occurred, no advantage or disadvantage occurred in particular genes.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotype networks are used to show the relationship among haplotypes, which are short pieces of a chromosome with traits that usually appear as a group or are linked. These create maps that show how individuals differ by SNPs, or single nucleotide polymorphisms.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The binomial expansion uses Pascal's triangle to predict how a family could have so many children with a certain phenotype or genotype thus allowing us to predict the probability of certain alleles occurring in that generation.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Populations in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium have no migration, no mutation, no selection, random mating, and a infinitely large population. If a population is not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium, then they must be evolving as a result of one of these five characteristics being broken. Most populations are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium.
phenomenonA Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonA[comment] I am interesting in the Hardy Weinberg equilibrium because I like using math to solve problems. I am interested in how seeing a increase in heterozygotes in a population can lead to hypothesis about how this is occurring. For example, we could say that heterozygotes for CF are being selected for in a malaria environment because this genotype also provide resistance to malaria. I like using this equation to figure out how it should be, see the deviations of the actual population, and then forming hypotheses to what characteristic is most likely being broken and causing the population to evolve.
phenomenonB Haplotype networks

knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Gene pools include all the genes in a population. Sexually reproducing organisms allow for variation of these genes in individuals because of meiosis and how they reproduce. Gene pools can be adjusted when natural selection occurs and organism's with the highest fitness will survive and reproduce. Additionally, migration and mutation will affect the allele frequencies in a population and thus alter the genes in a gene pool.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] These type of networks represent the genotypes that get passed on to generations, and we can study what we know to predict the ratios a population will be (heterozygous/homozygous).
explainConcepts[SQ002] The binomial expansion is an equation used to estimate the ratios of genotypes in a population. We may represent an allele (A) as the variable p, which is the ratio of its frequency (normally in decimals, hundredths out of one), and the other allele (a) as q (its ratio as well). If p + q = 1, then we may find either variable if we know one. This can be used for the amount of genes we are observing, where n may represent the total amount of genes, then we can say (p+q)^n = 1.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Hardy Weinberg Equilibrium uses binomial expansion to predict these ratios of genes, and this can be calculated for a series of generations. The Hardy Weinberg Equilibrium suggests that there is no mutation, no selection, no genetic drift, nor any gene flow. If we may assume these rules, then a population's possibly genotype frequencies may be calculated. If there is an observable change over generations, then the system is not in Hardy Weinberg Equilibrium, therefore some factor is favoring an allele (mutation, selection, gene flow, or genetic drift).
phenomenonA Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonA[comment] We have studied how blood type is not a type of selection observed, and therefore we may predict a populations blood type genotype using the Hardy Weinberg Equilibrium.
phenomenonB Haplotype networks
phenomenonB[comment] Haplotype networks demonstrate why a population must favor migration in order to lower inbreeding. Inbreeding may result in a higher chance of an unfavorable recessive genotype being homozygous. It can be observed in nature that most factors that lower the chance of inbreeding, show favorability for a population.
groupTime421 852.47

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Haplotype networks can be used as the factors for calculation the genotypes in a population. If we know the amount of individuals in a population that are either AA, Aa, or aa of a certain genotype, then we may be able to calculate the rest of the populations genotype using binomial expansion.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Using math, we can observe that binomial expansion helps us calculate the proportions of genes in a population. If we set a number "n" as our total number of genes (and knowing that for each individual, there are two of each gene because of homologous chromosomes), we may calculate that p (frequency of one allele of one gene) plus q (frequency of the other allele of same gene) should equal one, resulting in (p+q)^n = 1.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Hardy Weinberg equlibrium is a useful tool for measuring expected frequencies of genotypes in a population. The Hardy Weinberg equilibrium is a utilization of binomial expansion as long as four rules are met: there is no selection, no mutation, no gene flow, and no genetic drift.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Gene pools are the encompass the entire available genes/alleles of a population. When using binomial expansion, we may think of the gene pool as the "1" used in the equation. All possible frequencies of observed genes being studied are included in the gene pool of that population.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotype networks can reveal how closely related members of a population are. They are important because a haplotype is a set of genes that are linked in a region and thus are passed on together. So if individuals have the same haplotypes then they share many of the same genes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes can all be predicted through binomial expansion. Specifically, they can be predicted through the Hardy-Weinbeg Law. According to this Law, as long as a population is free from mutations and migrations, has random mating, is infinitely large, and each individual has the same chance of survival, then you can predict all of these frequencies if you know the frequency of just one allele or genotype. They can simply be predicted by plugging them into an equation and solving for the frequencies.
explainConcepts[SQ003] If a population is not in Hardy Weinberg Equilibrium then it is not staying the same fro generation to generation. This population could be producing new alleles from mutations, experiencing migration from individuals entering or leaving the population, experiencing genetic drift if it is a smaller population, or the individuals could engage in nonrandom mating. Also, natural selection would cause the population not to be in Hardy Weinberg Equlibrium and evolve.
phenomenonA Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonA[comment] I think it is interesting how populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways. I think of Darwin's finches and how there were several new species that came from what was to believed to originally be one species. So if you were to attempt to determine the frequencies for the population through the equation they would be incorrect. This proves that the new species that branched from one and were created through geographic isolation (migration) and natural selection shows that populations that are evolving are not in Hardy Weinberg equilbrium.
phenomenonB Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonB[comment] The fitness of an individual based off their inherited genes is an example of how selection can cause a population to evolve and keep it out of Hardy Weinberg equilibrium. For example, individuals with two mutant recessive alleles for Tay-Sachs disease will die before the age of four. Thus, they will not pass on their genes and have a poor fitness. This is an example of a population evolving and not meeting the criteria for Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotypes are groups of linked genes that are commonly inherited together because they are close together on the chromosome. These groupings allow geneticists to compile haplotype networks and find out where genes are on the chromosomes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Binomial expansion allows us to calculate and predict allele frequencies in populations. The Hardy Weinberg principle is rooted in this expansion, but goes a step further to allow us to identify the proportion of genotypes in the population (p squared is homozygous dominant individuals, 2pq is heterozygous individuals, p squared is homozygous recessive).
explainConcepts[SQ003] Hardy Weinberg equilibrium requires a large population, no new mutations, no natural selection, no movement in or out of the population, and random mating. If a population is not in this equilibrium, that means that one or more of these conditions are being violated. Hardy Weinberg equilibrium predicts that the allele frequencies will stay constant in future generations, but if a population is evolving (mutations, natural selection, non random mating), the allele frequencies will change from generation to generation. The alleles that are being selected for will increase in frequency, while the alternate alleles for that gene will decrease.
phenomenonA The frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes can be predicted using the binomial expansion.
phenomenonA[comment] Using binomial expansion in the context of Hardy Weinberg equilibrium is interesting to me because this formula gives such accurate predictions and allows us to predict the genotypes of members of a population we could not have discerned without the calculation. This happens when a trait is completely dominant, so it is impossible to distinguish between individuals that are heterozygous or homozygous dominant. Without statistical models to predict these frequencies, the proportion of genotypes in a population would b unknown.
phenomenonB Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonB[comment] I'm interested in instances of Hardy Weinberg disequilibrium because I feel like most populations would spend a majority (if not all) their time in disequilibrium because of the strict conditions required to be in equilibrium. At least on a larger scale, I feel like natural selection and evolution continues to slowly occur, so I feel like any population, given enough time, would violate one or more Hardy Weinberg conditions.
groupTime421 954.72

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Haplotype networks are useful in assessing the frequencies and transmission of genes in populations. These groups of linked genes tend to be inherited together, so by analyzing these frequencies we can asses what groups of traits are prevalent in which populations and then make predictions as to why these differences in frequencies between populations occur.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Binomial expansion is the base for the Hardy Weinberg equations, as well as useful in predicting the probability of two or more events occurring simultaneously in specific proportions. In terms of populations and allele frequencies, binomial expansion allows us to identify the frequencies of two or more alleles in a population as well as the frequencies of the different genotypes in the population.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium (meaning successive generations have changing allele frequencies) are violating one or more of the conditions. One of those conditions is no new mutations, and since mutations are the source of new alleles it makes sense that a population with new alleles is evolving. Another condition is that no alleles are selected for (no natural selection). If on allele was more adaptive or advantageous than the other alleles for that gene, natural selection would slowly increase the allele frequencu for the preferred trait.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Gene pools are the compilation of all the different alleles for genes in a certain population. While each individual will only get 2 alleles for each gene, the gene pool account for all the alleles for that gene in a population, which is much more than just the 2 alleles in a specific individual.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A haplotype network is a method to connect individuals to one another based on the unique set of gene sequences they have on their DNA, single nucleotide polymorphisms. Since these are inherited from parent to child, an established link between the two can be used to identify the distance of the relationship an individual might have with one another as well as the ancestry they might share.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Using the Hardy Weinberg equation, which assumes that under random mating, no migration, no genetic drift and no mutation in an infinitely large population, genotype and allele frequencies can be predicted for that population using a binomial expansion. Depending on the number of genes whose frequency you want to identify, more or less variables may be used to identify the homozygous dominant and recessive as well as the heterozygous in the population.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Because there are a set of assumptions that should be held for Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium to occur, which include no mutation, random mating, no migration, gene flow or genetic drift in an infinitely large population, if any or more than one of these conditions are not met, one can assume that evolution is occurring within a population as the frequency of alleles in a genotype will change.
phenomenonA The frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes can be predicted using the binomial expansion.
phenomenonA[comment] Using the binomial expansion, I can estimate whether or not the plants in my garden will have offspring that are homozygous or heterozygous for certain traits and whether or not the number that have those traits are in equilibrium

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotypes are sets of alleles from closely linked loci carried by an individual that are inherited together. Haplotype networks show the relationship among haplotypes. They can be used to compare individuals between populations to infer which ones are more closely related.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Binomial expansion can be used to predict different frequencies with the use of the Hardy-Weinberg equation which is p^2+2pq+q^2 = 1. The equation can be expanded to make predictions for multiple alleles. p+q=1 can be to determine the allele frequencies and this is squared to get the Hardy-Weinberg equation for frequencies of genotypes and phenotypes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] No population is actually in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium. In populations that would meet Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, there is no evolution. Without that, populations can experience genetic drift, mutation, gene flow and natural selection which could potentially change allele frequencies in a population.
phenomenonA Haplotype networks
phenomenonA[comment] Haplotype networks can be used to look at evolutionary history of populations. One interesting example of this would be how geneticists found a distinct Y chromosomes in many men throughout Asia that traced back to Genghis Khan.
phenomenonB Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonB[comment] It is interesting to see how natural selection can cause a large change in populations. One example I found interesting would be the Galapagos Island finches. One year when studied during a drought, it was found that the average beak size of the birds increased to help them better survive while beak size once again decreased when the drought had ended.
groupTime421 2797.58

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Haplotypes are sets of DNA variations that tend to be inherited together. Haplotype networks are used to show the relationships among these haplotypes. Individuals can share haplotypes and when this happens, it shows that they are closely related to each other. Haplotypes can be used to compare individuals between populations to see which populations are more closely related. Haplotype networks are very important in mapping evolutionary and geographical history against one another.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] The letter p can be used to represent the frequency of the dominant allele in a population and the letter q can be used to represent the frequency of the recessive allele and added together they will equal 1, p + q=1. When (p+q) are squared, using binomial expansion, this gives the equation P2 + 2pq + q2. This is the Hardy-Weinberg equation and can be used to determine genotype and phenotype frequencies of homozygous dominants, homozygous recessives and heterozygotes in a population that is in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Populations that are in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium must meet 5 conditions: infinite population, no immigration or emigration, random mating, no mutations and no natural selection. This is impossible in real life and populations are pushed by evolutionary influences such as gene flow, genetic drift, mutation and natural selection. Mutation increases diversity, natural selection has a null effect or decreases diversity, gene flow increases diversity within a population but decreases it between populations, and genetic drift decreases diversity.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] A gene pool is the total of all alleles possessed by the reproductive members of a population. Genes in a sexually reproducing population are continuously mixed and can change through time with the addition of different alleles. Many populations have a high degree of heterozygosity to have a “built-in” diversity Different populations will have different gene pools that correspond with the traits that are most successful in that area.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The haplotype network is a series of genes on a chromosome. If we know the distance between SNPs, microsatellites,indels or genes that consistanly are on the same position of a chromosome, we can use these known relative positions to figure out the relative distance of other genes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Using the Hardy-Weinburg equilibrium equation: p^2+2pq+q^2 and p+q=1 We can predict the allele frequency for a population in Hardy Weinberg Equilibrium. This is important because it can show hoe the effect of things like inbreeding and genetic isolation lead to higher heterozygosity and decreased variation.
explainConcepts[SQ003] No population can ACTUALLY be in hardy weinberg equilibrium, because the conditions require totally random mating, an infinitely large population, no mutation, and no immigration/emigration. So any given population experiences a small amount of mutations, but when these mutations are advantageous, the become reproduced and proliferated in the offspring of the original mutant. However if two of the same species had been separated by a river at some point and Population A acquired mutations independently from Population B, then eventually they would be too genetically different to create fertile offspring, thus resulting in two different species, thus evolution.
phenomenonA The frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes can be predicted using the binomial expansion.
phenomenonA[comment] I am studying anthropology and I find it interesting to see the effects of this in society. For example, the Fugate family in Kentucky, AKA the Blue family. Extensive inbreeding in this geographically isolated area has actually led to some members of this family having a blueish tint to their skin due to a mutation affecting the way oxygen is carried through their bodies.
phenomenonB Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonB[comment] This is also also an interesting phenomenon that makes me think of the immigration of Asian population over the land bridge that used to connect Asia to North America. So modern Asians, North Americans, and South Americans all descended from a common group of people. However, "full bred" North Americans cannot seem to grow facial hair while "full bred" South Americans can, and so can Asians. If they went from Asia through North America and down to South America, why is the population that is sandwiched in the middle the only one that cannot grow facial hair?

knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Hardy weinberg equilibrium uses binomial expansion to predict the change in allele frequency in future generations using and equation that models a population in equilibrium. Because nothing can really be in equilibrium, this can never be 100% correct, but it is still a useful tool for modeling changes in hetero and homozygosity over time.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Mutations are always occurring, mating is selective, immigration does occur, and populations do not have infinite numbers or resources. So bearing that in mind, mutations occur in pretty much every individual and they breed and reproduce usually in an exponential pattern, so all of those mutations over time have a collective snowball effect. So for example, corn today does not look like corn from 20000 ya because of those collective mutations and other selective factors.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Gene pools consist of all the alleles in a mating population.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A haplotype is a unique sequence of bases over an area of the genome. People who share a haplotype are thought to be closely related since they have the same sequence for that entire region in the genome. We can use haplotypes to compare individuals between populations in order to decide which populations are most closely related to which others/which evolved more recently.
explainConcepts[SQ002] We can use the equation p2 +2pq+q2 to determine the frequency of alleles and genotypes in a population that is experiencing Hardy Weinberg equilibrium. p=the number of dominant alleles p2= the number of homozygous dominant individuals (since each individual has 2 dominant alleles) 2pq=the number of heterozygotes in the population. There is 2 because either the male or the female could pass either the dominant or the recessive gene to their progeny, so here are 2 ways to get a heterozygous genotype. q=the number of recessive alleles q2= the number of homozygous recessive individuals (since each individual would have 2 recessive alleles)
explainConcepts[SQ003] Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium must be violating on of the criteria for a HW population. It could be a very small population that is inbreeding or undergoing nonrandom mating, mutations could have occurred, selection could be acting on a particular trait, and gene flow or genetic drift could also be occurring.
phenomenonA Haplotype networks
phenomenonA[comment] This relates to phylogenetic trees as we can map the evolutionary history of a species in regards to its relationship to other closely related species. It allows us to determine the relatedness between species.
phenomenonB Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonB[comment] Few populations are actually in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium since in nature almost all of the Hardy Weinberg criteria are broken. However, it is very interesting that while many populations cannot be in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium, genes (such as ABO blood groups) can be experiencing HW equilibrium.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotype network is series of traits or allele on chromosome or series of short piece of chromosome that is typically linked and generally very stable. Haplotype network is used to find relatedness between population. Haplotype network must be in middle not too long not too short, which shows accurate and informative information regarding the relatedness of individuals to others
explainConcepts[SQ002] Under "ideal" population of hardy-weindberg, allele frequency in the population is found by p+q=1, where p is dominant alleles in population and 1 is recessive allele in population. (p+q)^n=1 where is n is number of alleles in the population. so for 2 alleles, individual frequency can be found by p2+2pq+q2=1, where p2 is homozygous dominant, 2pq is heterozugous or carrier and homozygous recessive individuals. X-linked individual frequency=allele frequency, can be found by p+q=1 as hemizygosity lacks one of the X chromosome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Factors the influence the evolution to occur are natural selection, sexual selection or nonrandom mating, gene flow, genetic drift, and mutation. Natural selection is when one variation of trait is favored more over the other describing their fitness, which is defined by survival and reproduction, they contribute more to the next generation, evolving the population over time. Gene flow is when immigration or emigration influence the gene frequency, leading to evolution. genetic drift when small population looses gene variation for very long period of time, genetic bottleneck. mutation introduces new allele to population. non random mating where selection on the choice of mate. This all evolution leads to speciation which is reproduction isolation.
phenomenonA Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonA[comment] The factors of evolution that influenced leading to many speciation such of common ancestor hominids to neanderthals, homo sapiens.
phenomenonB Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonB[comment] Neanderthals, denvions, homo sapiens were able to interbreed when they excited so what made them believe that they were different species even there was no reproductive isolation.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotype networks allow us to see how populations not only evolved, but also how the populations moved geographically based on examining haplotypes, which are characteristic to each population.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Using the formulas (p+q)^2=1 and p+q=1, where p is the frequency of one allele and q is the frequency of the other, we can predict the frequency of alleles, genotypes, and even phenotypes. As long as we are given one of the frequencies, we can determine the others through these two formulas. Calculating these frequencies in this manner, however, requires Hardy Weinberg assumptions, so most real-life frequencies cannot be determined through this accurately.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Because Hardy Weinberg equilibrium postulates that the population in question must be under certain conditions that prevent evolution, we know that if a population is not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium it must be breaking one of the 5 assumptions, which indicates that it must be evolving
phenomenonA Haplotype networks
phenomenonA[comment] These are so important for phylogeography, the science of mapping of evolutionary history against geographical history
phenomenonB Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonB[comment] Obviously, Hardy Weinberg is deeply rooted in evolutionary theory, but though it's obvious, it should be noted that it clearly maps out what it takes for a population to evolve, and it gives us a clear determining factor for whether microevolution is occurring or not.

groupTime420 190.87

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotype networks are groups of closely linked alleles that are inherited as a unit. Haplotype networks that consist of SNPs can serve as markers for specific chromosome regions. These regions can then be used to identify other regions that are may contain genes linked with specific diseases. This technology is incredibly important because it allows scientists to locate what gene mutations are linked cause illnesses such as cystic fibrosis and schizophrenia.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes can all be predicted by using binomial expansion.(p+q)^2=p^2+2pq+q^2=1. p stands for the allele frequency of the dominant allele and q represents the allele frequency of the recessive allele. These numbers can then be used to calculate the number of homogeneous dominant, heterogeneous, and homogeneous recessive organisms there are in a population. This is important because it allows scientist to determine a lot of information about a given population. Also, when used in successive generations, binomial expansion can be used to determine whether or not the population is evolving in regards to a specific gene.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways depending on what phenomenon and is occurring and for what reason. The conditions that must be met in order for a population to be in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium include: large population size, natural selection, no mutation, no migration,and no natural selection. When one of these is occurring/not occurring allele frequencies begin to change and evolution occurs. This is an important topic to understand because it is the basis for why populations evolve and change and sometimes become new species (speciation).
phenomenonA Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonA[comment] The topic of Hard Weinberg equilibrium in regards to evolution is an extremely important biological phenomenon because it allows us to determine how and when a population is evolving. For all evolving populations, one or more of the five Hardy Weinberg criteria listed above are broken.
phenomenonB The frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes can be predicted using the binomial expansion.
phenomenonB[comment] This topic is important because it allows scientists to make a variety of calculations from one set of known values. Knowing the frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes of different generations of the same population allows us to determine whether or not a population is evolving. If allele frequencies are changing, it can be concluded that at least one of the 5 Hardy Weinberg criteria are not being met. Therefore, this topic relates to evolution and speciation, two important biological phenomenon.

When a gene pool is small, the population has very little genetic diversity meaning its individuals are very genetically similar. Reduced genetic diversity can be an issue however because it can reduce the biological fitness of a population.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotype networks show the relationship among haplotypes. Haplotypes are a set of alleles from a closely linked locus that are inherited as a unit. They can be used to trace human ancestries.
explainConcepts[SQ002] By using the equation p^2+2pq+q^2=1, it is possible to determine the frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes in a population. p^2 is the frequency of the homozygous dominant individuals. 2pq is the frequency of the heterozygous individuals, and q^2 is the frequency of the homozygous recessive individuals. By using p+q=1 (p=dominant, q=recessive) you can find the frequency of different alleles.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Hardy Weinberg Equilibrium has 5 stipulations. 1-Non random mating must occur. 2-Infinite population size 3-No migration in or out 4-no mutation 5-no selection So populations not in hardy-weinberg equilibrium are evolving by natural selection and gaining new alleles by mutation.
phenomenonA Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonA[comment] Populations that aren't in hardy-weinberg equilibrium may be affected by genetic drift, gene flow, natural selection, nonrandom mating, and gene flow. Populations affected by genetic drift can cause changes in allele frequencies in small populations. The founder effect occurs when a group of individuals has been separated from the larger population, and the genes that they have are the genes that they're descendants will have. Genes from the larger population are left out, and this could eventually result in speciation.
phenomenonB The frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes can be predicted using the binomial expansion.
phenomenonB[comment] This is important to know the frequency of genotypes in a population. Often times people mistake a homozygous genotype for being the most dominant in a population, but typically the heterozygotes have the largest frequency.

explainConcepts[SQ003] If populations are in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium, then no evolution can be occurring. When populations are in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium, and then shift out of Hardy Weinberg equilibrium, some form of evolution must be occurring. All of these are a necessity for the model.

In addition, these differences, if not many, can also portray the closeness between the haplotypes and this network is a great way to trace back events or compare the relationship between two species. This network has been used to determine the possible origination of humans which claims that the "Eve" of humans lived in Africa when Pangea existed. This network is highly crucial in determining similarities and differences within a species or amongst multiple species and with that information a possible hypothesis could be created explaining the network's results.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Binomial expansion is a method that utilizes Pascal's Triangle and probability to determine the frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes including the gender of an offspring or multiple offsprings. This tool is crucial for multiple reasons since it gives an individual to approximate the percentage of outcome X to occur within Y trials. Binomial Expansion takes the general form of (a+b)^n where n is the total number of independent events or outcomes and 'a' and 'b' are the chances of outcome a and outcome b. Although this is basic probability, I sometimes get confused on how to utilize this mathematical model in problems, but I do understand the concept and the importance of this.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The Hardy Weinberg Equilibrium states that certain conditions must be met be fore ideal results are put into action. The conditions are the following: no mutation, no migration or immigration, no selection, random mating, and an infinitely large population. These conditions correspond to ideal results in which allele frequencies of both the dominant and recessive allele will remain constant overtime throughout generations. This concept can also be used for sex linked genes but with a slight variation. If the Hardy Weinberg law is discredited through the violation of at least one condition that was earlier stated, then the population(s) is left subject to evolutionary influences (both micro-evolution and macro-evolution) which results in variation from one population to the next. These evolutionary factors include mutation, gene flow, genetic drift and even speciation, thus, creating differentiation a between populations. This law consists of two equations that can be used to calculate frequencies of an allele or the frequencies of homozygous dominant and recessive and heterozygotes.
phenomenonA Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonA[comment] I find the Hardy Weinberg equilibrium interesting since it depicts results that only occur in ideal environments since the conditions required for this law to predict the results of populations are not usually complied with and are instead defied. Yet, this law is used to create assumptions of an ideal population or to apply the results to a non-ideal or real populations since at least one condition, if not more, is violated. This notion intrigues me since I understand the use for this principle logically, but the fact that reality always overcomes ideality in terms of the Hardy Weinberg Law. Furthermore in reality since one condition is at least defied, that means evolutionary processes do occur that do change the allele frequencies throughout generations within a population and amongst other populations. These evolutionary processes include mutation, gene flow caused by migration or immigration, or even genetic drift such as the bottleneck effect and can change the alleles frequencies over time through random and non-random means.
phenomenonB Haplotype networks
phenomenonB[comment] I find haplotype networks interesting since I never knew about the existence of such a model before a week when it was first introduced in class. This tool is an important genetic map that allows scientists to form hypothesis on the basis of certain differences in microsatellites (repeated sequences), SNPs ( point mutations), and even indels which are points of deletions or insertions within one's genome. I am unsure about the limitations of this map, but it may be even used to construct phylogenetic trees. Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Haplotype networks are means to show relationships between haplotypes by depicting the differences between haplotype A and haplotype B by the number of mutations such as indels and SNP's and/or repeated sequences called microsatellites. This network complex does not show the differences between only two haplotypes, but it can show the differences amongst many haplotypes by creating branches to depict the haplotype being studied. This model is powerful in the sense that it can trace one back to fascinating historical events and it can show the close relationship amongst three haplotypes which consist of the genome sequence that are relatively the same with the exception of certain mutations that have arises within the sequence over the years.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] The binomial expansion is highly used mathematical model that can determine the probability of X circumstances occurring. In this, one can calculate the approximated percentage of frequency of alleles, genotypes, phenotypes, and even the sex of the offspring(s). I do understand the concepts and the importance of the binomial expansion and the probability behind it, but certain problems do confuse me and I am not able to solve them. I understand that this is based on basic probability questions that can become complex when introducing multiple variables, but nonetheless it is a crucial model that numerous geneticists use.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The Hardy Weinberg Law states that allele frequencies will remain constant throughout generations because of the lack of selectional and evolutionary forces that are at play. However if any of the conditions are violated, then these forces will affect the population(s). These conditions include the following: no mutations, no selection, no migration or immigration, random mating, and an infinitely large population. Since at least one condition is violated in real populations, the selectional pressure and evolutionary processes do occur that can result in variation in one population from another. These processes include the presence of mutations, gene flow caused by the introduction or the reduction of alleles within the gene pool due to the migration or immigration of species, or even genetic drift which are random events that occur within the environment such as the bottleneck effect and the founder effect. Many of these factors create differences within and amongst populations and an even lead to speciation in certain circumstances. In addition, one population is not necessarily subject to all of the evolutionary factors at once or within a period of time since evolution, itself, takes many generations to occur to create differentiation amongst populations.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Gene pools consist of all alleles that exist within a population that lives within the same relative area. The greater the variation in the gene pool, the better likely the population can survive in times of drastic environmental changes. Furthermore, gene pools are highly affected by selection pressure and evolution thus implying the gene pool can change over time in the event of some circumstance occurring. Although an individual can only carry two alleles of a gene, the gene pool is a notion that "contains" a list of all the alleles within that entire population for all the genes.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A haplotype is a set of alleles from closely linked loci carried by an individual that are inherited as a unit. Individuals that share a haplotype are inferred to be closely related to another. Haplotype networks are used to compare individuals haplotypes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] When 1 of 2 outcomes can occur in a number of trials, the probability of the outcome of several trails can be predicted using binomial expansion. (p + q)^n=1 is the equation. p stands for probability of one event, q stands for probability of another event, and n stands for the number of trials.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Under Hardy Weinburg equilibrium individuals of all genotypes have equal rates of survival and equal reproductive success (no selection), no new alleles are created (no mutation), no migration, large population, and random mating. If one of these are not met then the population evolves in a different way via individuals from other populations mating or migrating and alleles are created/converted to new alleles via mutation leading to new phenotypes and genotypes.
phenomenonA Haplotype networks
phenomenonA[comment] Using haplotype networks geneticists have found Ghengis Khan's Y chromosome in a person living today. Using haplotype networks has also shown that most people have originated from another country which I find very interesting.
phenomenonB The frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes can be predicted using the binomial expansion.
phenomenonB[comment] In class we are studying cystic fibrosis. Using binomial expansion, we can calculate the probability of a family having a child with or without cystic fibrosis. One day I would like to be a doctor so I think this could be very useful in my career.

knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that the frequency of alleles, genotypes, and phenotypes can be predicted using binomial expansion because it factors in each probability of each chance happening in the equation. (p + q)^n=1 can predict that probability of the outcome of several trials when 1 of 2 outcomes can occur in a number of trials. This can be very helpful to determine whether people will have a certain amount of children that are affected with a certain genetic disease.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that populations under Hardy Weinberg equilibrium have no selection, no migration, no mutation, random mating, and a large population. If these assumptions are not met then the population is evolving in a way that incorporates mutations to alleles leading to new genotypes and phenotypes, migration of new individuals to new populations leading to exposure of new genes, and there would be loss of some genotypes since it wouldn't have equal rates of survival.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that the genetic information carried by members of a population constitutes that population's gene pool. A large gene pool means there is a lot of genetic diversity in the population meaning this population can survive selection. A small gene pool can lead to extinction of the population and decreased fitness.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A haplotype is a unique set of gene sequences or set of single nucleotide polymorphisms on the same chromosome. A haplotype network can be used to compare haplotypes in a population and across different populations.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The Hardy-Weinberg Law can be used to describe allele and gene frequencies in a "ideal" population. If the population is ideal, the population is infinitely large, has random mating, and is not affected by mutation, migration, or natural selection. If the population is ideal, you can use binomial expansion to solve for allele and gene frequencies. To find allele frequencies, you would use the equation p+q=1, where p=the dominant allele and q=the recessive allele. To determine gene frequencies you would square the first equation to get p^2+2pq+q^2=1. P^2 would represent the homozygous dominant gene frequency, 2pq would represent the heterozygous gene frequency, and q^2 would represent the homozygous recessive gene frequency.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Populations not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are not infinitely large and do not always randomly mate. Populations not in HW eq are also susceptible to mutation, migration, and natural selection. (They can be affected by genetic drift, gene mutation, gene flow and natural selection.)
phenomenonA Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonA[comment] In parts of the world where malaria is highly threatening, there are higher frequencies of the sickle cell alleles in the populations. Sickle cell alleles have been selected to help these populations survive the negative effects of malaria.
phenomenonB Haplotype networks
phenomenonB[comment] Haplotype networks have been used to trace human origins back to Africa by comparing the haplotypes of different world populations.
groupTime421 2146.31

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that haplotypes are a set of unique gene sequences across a genome. I understand that you can compare haplotypes of individuals in a population to gain information about that population such as what evolutionary factors have affected that population. I understand that you can compare haplotypes of populations to other populations to create a haplotype network. I understand that haplotype networks are useful to infer how clolsely related different populations are and also to determine their evolutionary history.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that the Hardy Weinberg law is useful to find general allele and gene frequencies in a population. I understand that in HW eq, the population must be "ideal" which means that it is infinitely large, randomly mates, and is not affected by mutation, migration, or selection. I understand that to find allele frequencies you use the equation p+q=1, and to find gene frequencies you use the equation p^2+2pq+q^2+1. I understand that normal populations are not in HW eq, but you can use the equations above to find the ideal frequencies and compare them to the actual frequencies of the population to infer the evolutionary processes that might be affecting the population.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that populations in real life are not infinitely large and do not always randomly mate. I understand that genetic drift, gene mutation, gene flow, and natural selection can all affect the allele and gene frequencies of a population.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that gene pools is the set of all genes and genetic information of a population (usually within the same species). I understand that the allele and gene frequencies of gene pools can be evaluated to gain insight on the evolution of that population.

explainConcepts[SQ002] Binomial expansion is a way of predicting frequency of alleles, genotypes and phenotypes by using this equation P = n!/x! (n-x)! p^x q^n-x This is an easy way to determine all possibilities for a given set of unordered events.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The Hardy Weinberg law states what happens to an allele and genotype frequencies in an ideal population that is large and randomly mating. If a population meets the criteria that 1) the frequencies of alleles in the gene pool do not change over time and 2) If two alleles at a locus are considered and after one generation of random dating then they are said to be in Hardy Weinberg.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Haplotypes show the interconnectedness of haplotype networks. They can be used to establish the extent of relationships. The network looks like a sentence diagram and maps out the likes and differences between genomes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Frequency is predicted using the equation (p+q)^2. p is the dominant allele. q is the recessive allele. The equation can be expanded to give the number of homozygous and heterozygous individuals in the population by the equation p^2 + 2pq + q^q = 1
explainConcepts[SQ003] If a population does not fit the above equations, then it breaks one or more of the assumptions of h-w equilibrium. These are no mutation, no migration, no gene flow, infinite population, and random mating.
phenomenonA Haplotype networks
phenomenonA[comment] The lineage of the Mongolians was interesting. A man in Florida traced his Y gene back to the ancient leader. That was interesting.
phenomenonB Populations that are not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium are evolving in different ways.
phenomenonB[comment] Populations are almost always evolving, but the different ways in which they evolve can be determined by working backwards from this concept
